Manibus. Two altars, with the inscription D. M. (Dis Manibus), were erected to the spirit of the dead. The Manes were the spirits of the departed, which after the death of the body possessed an influence over their friends and kinsfolk, and therefore must be propitiated by offerings. It was even believed that the spirits settled in the lower world could at intervals visit the earth. This idea is common to all ages and tribes. It is the basis of the religion and even the life of the Chinese, while in raees lower 111 1110 scale the belief in and worship of the spirit of the dead is so common that some have sought in it the first step towards religious feelings.
